import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;
public class java_52115_SocketServer_A03 {    // This is a unique program that uses vanilla socket programming and security-sensitive operations related to A03_Injection only, using standard libraries in Java; ie., no external frameworks/libs like Spring or Hibernate are used here  . It does not use JSSE classes nor SSLContext.
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {   // Starts the server on port number (default is local machine's default Port:12345). The method accepts an integer argument representing this, which defaults to localhost’s arbitrary chosen available TCP/IP port if not supplied.
        ServerSocket welcomeSocket = new ServerSocket(8096);   // Create a server socket on the specified IP address and ports (in other words: listen for connections at that location) – here we will use loopback interface, which means our client should connect to us as well because TCP/IP stack is not involved.
        while(true){    // We keep this code in an infinite循环 so server can stay alive forever and the clients won't be able stop it with Ctrl+C . This could also just become a part of some application logic which you will have to implement yourself later, but for simplicity purposes here we are using loop.
            Socket connectionSocket = welcomeSocket.accept();    // Accepts an incoming client socket request   – this is blocking (i mean: it waits until there’s something new in the input stream of our current thread) . Once a call to accept() returns, that means one and only one client has connected into server at some point - we need then have control over which connection made on what side.
            // We create OutputStream for sending data back or forth between clients & servers – now is your turn (if you want) :). Let's say after this line it would be our responsibility to handle each client by reading from the input stream of socket, send a response and then closing connection with that specific connected party.
        }   // End while loop when server stops working properly using Ctrl+C command on terminal or program itself will stop if not handled in case where there is no other action performed within this method as far it runs until end the JVM gets stopped by OS (like for example through shutdown hooks, etc) 
    }//End main function. It'll be invoked at application start and would handle all incoming requests to server   according client’s behaviour - how he wants data from & send back response in that way until it will not work properly due to any reason (like JVM stopping by OS, some external event etc).
} //End class VanillaSocketServer.  It'll be unique program and does only socket programming with security related operations regarding A03_Injection which uses standard libraries Java built-in as well third party libs not used are excluded from this example for simplicity purposes but would need to implement in full if required by your project